Cheese is a dairy product derived from milk that is produced in a wide range of flavors, textures, and forms. It is made by coagulating the milk protein casein, usually from the milk of cows, goats, sheep, or buffalo. During production, milk is usually acidified, and adding rennet causes the proteins to coagulate. The solid curds are then separated from the liquid whey and pressed into final form.

Blueberries, tiny yet potent, are a nutritional powerhouse. Loaded with antioxidants, they help neutralise harmful free radicals, safeguarding our body's cells from damage. Rich in fibre, they assist digestion and promote a healthy gut. Their abundant Vitamin C and K content contribute to our overall wellbeing. The anthocyanins present enhance memory and brain function, whilst their anti-inflammatory properties help reduce the risk of chronic conditions. They can be consumed fresh or utilised in salads, as garnishes or blended into smoothies. Their delightful taste also makes them a favourite choice for desserts like blueberry ice pops, adding a healthy twist to indulgence.
Benefits

    Blueberries are loaded with antioxidants, which help neutralise harmful free radicals and prevent cell damage.
    They are rich in fibre, aiding in digestion and promoting a healthy gut.
    Blueberries are a good source of Vitamin C and K, which are essential for overall well-being.
    The anthocyanins in blueberries can help enhance brain function.
    They possess anti-inflammatory properties

 
 
 
Storage and Uses

Avoid rinsing berries directly under the tap as the force of the water can damage them. Instead, immerse them in a bowl of cold water and let them drain.
